<div id="review_4237935857" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4237935857" />
    <a title="Evan Micheals" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32281217-evan-micheals"><img alt="Evan Micheals" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1402816068p2/32281217.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4237935857?book_show_action=true">Dec 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Evan Micheals" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Evan Micheals" href="/user/show/32281217-evan-micheals">Evan Micheals</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4237935857" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16080375026911990749">I had not previously read any work of Christopher Hitchens and he keeps on being referenced by people who I have great respect for as a writer and thinker. I have a project to read everything Geoerge Orwell has written before I die and with each work I find what a profound and masterful writer he is. Each book makes a significant impact on me. This seemed like a good book to begin with Christopher Hitchens and gain an even deeper appreciation of Eric Blair (Orwell).<br/><br/>The book is well written and i</span>
  <span id="freeText16080375026911990749" style="display:none">I had not previously read any work of Christopher Hitchens and he keeps on being referenced by people who I have great respect for as a writer and thinker. I have a project to read everything Geoerge Orwell has written before I die and with each work I find what a profound and masterful writer he is. Each book makes a significant impact on me. This seemed like a good book to begin with Christopher Hitchens and gain an even deeper appreciation of Eric Blair (Orwell).<br /><br />The book is well written and is not a puff piece going out of its way to provide the best case for the accusations that Orwell would be judged as a anti-semitic, homophobic and sexist by modern sensibilities (whilst inferring the potential Orwell may have had homosexual tendencies himself). I feel Orwell would have approved.<br /><br />Hitchens give context to Orwell’s relationships with women when writing about his mother and Aunts “he derived a firm impression that women did not like men, that they looked upon them as a sort of large ugly, smelly &amp; ridiculous animal, who maltreated women in every way, above all by forcing their attentions upon them. It was pressed deep into his consciousness, to remain there till he was abt 20, that sexual intercourse gives pleasure only to the man” (p 113). How many young men are given such an impression growing up by the women in there lives, especially in our times when a stupid father is a sitcom trope. Loathing of men has become a theme of the Kremlin/Harvard elite. Hitchen’s leaves the reader an impression that Orwell had an aversion to masculine females and effeminate males.<br /><br />When speaking about the authoritarian (Stalinist) left “what was entirely unmistakable was the atmosphere of a society where individual life is absolutely pointless and where everything that is not absolutely compulsory is absolutely forbidden” (p 66). I see this in contemporary society that there are certain views that the bourgeois citizen must have. We live in a time of polite conformity, when contrarian views must not be held, especially in polite society. We socially cancel those who express what is forbidden.<br /><br />“Marxism in the twentieth century did produce its Andres Nin as well as its Kim II Sung. It’s something more than an irony that so many calling themselves leftists have been either too stupid or too compromised to recognise this, or have actually been twisted enough to prefer the second example to the first” (p 68). The Nin’s and the Trotsky’s never gained power, and we cannot judge if things would have gone better under them. I formerly identified strongly with the left and the far left, and happily saw myself as a Marxist. The one issue of importance to me is free speech, and that no longer appears safe with the Identitarian Marxist Left. At least the Capitalist only want to control money.<br /><br />I get the impression Orwell would had approved of this. Orwell most wanted to tell the truth as he saw it, and this is what Hitchens does with Orwell. Eric Blair was a complex and flawed man trying to make sense of what he saw in human nature. He could only tell his own perspective. He did not suffer sycophants or fools and clearly saw the dangers of totalitarianism. Eric Blair’s writing helps me make meaning of my own time. I think we might have got on well. Hitchens is a strong intellect who can write well and gave a good case of ‘Why Orwell Matters’.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16080375026911990749" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


