  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4256025919" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4256025919" />
    <a title="Andrew Carr" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17763301-andrew-carr"><img alt="Andrew Carr" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1544869243p2/17763301.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4256025919?book_show_action=true">Sep 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrew Carr" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrew Carr" href="/user/show/17763301-andrew-carr">Andrew Carr</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4256025919" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7789687230861028249">This is a short book of essays by one of the master essayists of our time, on one of the master essayists of the 20th century. There is a definate sense of admiration, envy, and perhaps even pathos in Hitchens take on Orwell.<br/><br/>What struck me in this (my second) reading was the argument that Orwells &apos;power of facing&apos; (as George put it) was grounded in an &apos;ambivalence&apos; about different groups. In the sense of being torn, of seeing the two sides of the coin. That Orwell was not simply the man who iden</span>
  <span id="freeText7789687230861028249" style="display:none">This is a short book of essays by one of the master essayists of our time, on one of the master essayists of the 20th century. There is a definate sense of admiration, envy, and perhaps even pathos in Hitchens take on Orwell.<br /><br />What struck me in this (my second) reading was the argument that Orwells 'power of facing' (as George put it) was grounded in an 'ambivalence' about different groups. In the sense of being torn, of seeing the two sides of the coin. That Orwell was not simply the man who identified the cruel heart of communism, but did so as an ardent socialist. That Orwell wrote the great defence of english common sense and common language, while a man who detested its colonial nature and elite dishonesty. That Orwell could see the flaws of the oppressed as clearly as those of the oppressor and yet knew clearly which side deserved empathy and support.<br /><br />We often think of intellectual honesty as simply the courage to critique. Indeed, many make such criticism their life's purpose. But today we also see the hollowness of such an approach. The sheer dishonesty of treating the entire world in shades of black and white where those with power are (insert your preferred critique) and those without should never be discussed lest we "punch down". But the superficiality of this approach helps explain why it never quite lands as criticism, and is even less successful as a work of political persuasion. <br /><br />We think of intellectual honesty as the ability to cut through. To get to the core. But the truth is, it's very easy to say 'this group is entirely defined by these attributes'. Particularly when those we dislike are tagged with vice, those we do with virtue. But we all feel the tug at our elbow that this is not the whole story, even as our fingers storm across the keyboard in condemnation. Perhaps a sense of ambivalence - again in being torn rather than un-engaged - is more honest.<br /><br />A short, enjoyable read by a great stylist.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7789687230861028249" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

