  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2168467020" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2168467020" />
    <a title="Kusaimamekirai" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33921897-kusaimamekirai"><img alt="Kusaimamekirai" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591523190p2/33921897.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2168467020?book_show_action=true">Nov 07, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kusaimamekirai" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kusaimamekirai" href="/user/show/33921897-kusaimamekirai">Kusaimamekirai</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2168467020" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12889171391439738103"> I love Christopher Hitchens for his acerbic wit, fiercely independent thinking. There are times in this book, and others of his, that he goes on obscure literary or philosophical tangents that I can&apos;t follow and yet he always comes back to his argument with precision and clarity. <br/> In his spirited defense of George Orwell from his modern day critics, Hitchens does much of the same. Critics have accused Orwell of being A virulently anti-communist informer, anti-homosexual, and a misogynist, among</span>
  <span id="freeText12889171391439738103" style="display:none"> I love Christopher Hitchens for his acerbic wit, fiercely independent thinking. There are times in this book, and others of his, that he goes on obscure literary or philosophical tangents that I can't follow and yet he always comes back to his argument with precision and clarity. <br /> In his spirited defense of George Orwell from his modern day critics, Hitchens does much of the same. Critics have accused Orwell of being A virulently anti-communist informer, anti-homosexual, and a misogynist, among other things. <br /> Hitchens doesn't try to make Orwell into a saint here (Orwell regrettably was very homophobic and misogynistic in his writings) however he does paint a picture of Orwell which shows his value for us in the 21st century and beyond.<br /> This value lies mainly in Orwell's use of language and unwillingness to allow euphemisms and subterfuge to pollute discourse. Orwell believed that allowing such language paved the way for fascism and autocrats. <br /> Overall this is a balanced view of a man, written by a man, that society needs now more than ever. Or as Hitchens writes:<br /><br />"What he illustrates, by his commitment to language as the partner of truth, is that 'views' do not really count; that it matters not what you think but how you think; and that politics are relatively unimportant, while principles have a way of ensuring, as do the few irreducible individuals who maintain allegiance to them."</span>
  <a data-text-id="12889171391439738103" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


